{"cursor":"3979","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Pagophagia' is a form of the disorder pica involving the compulsive consumption\nof ice or iced drinks. {{cite journal |pmid=1410082 |title=Pagophagia, or\ncompulsive ice consumption: a historical perspective |author=Parry-Jones, B.\n|publisher= Psychol Med |date=August 1993 |volume=22 |issue=3 |pages=561â71\n|journal=Psychological Medicine}} It has been associated with iron\ndeficiency anemia, {{cite journal |author=de Los Angeles L, de Tournemire\nR, Alvin P |title=Pagophagia: pica caused by iron deficiency in an adolescent\n|journal=Arch Pediatr. |volume=12 |issue=2 |pages=215â7 |year=2005\n|month=February |pmid=15694552 |doi=\n10.1016/j.arcped.2004.11.022|url=}} and shown to respond to\niron supplementation, {{cite web |url=http://online.wsj.com/article/SB12016-\n5510390727145.html?mod=todays_us_nonsub_page_one |title=Chew This Over:\nMunchable Ice Sells Like Hot Cakes |author=Ilan Brat |work=Wall Street Journal\n|date=January 30, 2008 |accessdate=2008-01-31}} leading some\ninvestigators to postulate that some forms of pica may be the result of\nnutritional deficiency. Chewing ice may lessen pain in glossitis related to iron\ndeficiency anemia. Mesa, Ruben, MD. [http://www.mayoclinic.com/health/chewing-\nice/AN01278 Craving and chewing ice: A sign of Anemia?], MayoClinic.com.\nHowever, the American Dental Association recommends not chewing ice because it\ncan crack teeth; instead ice should be allowed to melt in the mouth. The\nAmerican Dental Association. [http://www.colgate.com/app/Colgate/US/OC/Informat-\nion/ADA/Article_2006_07_ChewOnThis.cvsp Chew on This: Crunching Ice Can Be Bad\nfor Your Teeth.] colgate.com, 19 July 2006.\n\nFolk wisdom (and some early investigators) maintained that pica reflected an\nappetite to compensate for nutritional deficiencies, such as low iron or zinc.\nSome forms of pica (as in pregnant women who are iron deficient) can be treated\nby supplementing the nutrient. Gavin, Mary L., MD.\n[http://kidshealth.org/parent/nutrition_fit/nutrition/pica.html Pica.]\nKidsHealth for Parents. December 2007.\n\nLater research has demonstrated that the substances ingested generally do not\nprovide the mineral or nutrient in which patients are deficient. As the people\nstart eating nonfoods, pica can also cause the nutritional deficiencies with\nwhich it is associated. In one case study,\npagophagia was reported to cause iron deficiency anemia. At the same time,\nhowever, the researchers suggested that chewing ice may benefit stomatitis and\nglossitis. The nutrients obtained from nonfoods such as soil or ice\nwill vary widely depending on geographic location. For example, ice made from\nhard water will contain more minerals, especially calcium and magnesium, but\nsimply drinking the water will provide the same minerals.\n","linknr":264,"url":"pagophagia","recorded":1376424151,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Pagophagia&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Pagophagia&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pagophagia","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.visualEditor.viewPageTarget.noscript&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#